    "input": "{\"stored\": true, \"facts_extracted\": 1}",
    "output": "Before the system performs any context\u2011compaction, you should **archive** every tool\u2011output that is still residing only in the chat transcript as *verbatim evidence*. In practice that means:\n\n| Action | What to do | Why it matters |\n|--------|------------|----------------|\n| 1\ufe0f\u20e3 **Persist the raw output** | Use `memory_add` (or the equivalent persistence API) to store a copy of the tool\u2019s `stdout`, `stderr`, or the returned JSON exactly as it appears in the chat. | Guarantees that the output survives the compaction cycle and can be retrieved later for audit, debugging, or compliance. |\n| 2\ufe0f\u20e3 **Annotate with context** | Include a short note about which tool created it, when it was called, and any relevant parameters. | Helps future agents or users understand the conditions that produced the output. |\n| 3\ufe0f\u20e3 **Avoid trimming or summarising** | Do **not** summarise or paraphrase the output before storing. | The requirement explicitly asks for \u201cverbatim evidence\u201d, not a digest. |\n| 4\ufe0f\u20e3 **Audit trail** | If your environment supports a change\u2011log or audit table, record that a compaction\u2011pre\u2011handler ran and archived the output. | Provides an extra layer of traceability. |\n\nSo, if a tool like `sandbox_execute` just returned a JSON payload, you would immediately call `memory_add` with that payload (or store it in a dedicated \u201ctool\u2011output\u201d bucket), optionally tagging it with the tool name and timestamp. Only after that has successfully staged the output for persistence should the compaction routine proceed.",
